<p style="text-align:justify;">beginning of July; the others follow in proportion to the distance they have to go; and arrive at their several destinations before the taking of the ice &#8211; At the breaking up of which they measure back the same route and arrive at the Grand Portage from the beginning of June to the latter end of August.  The present Returns of the North West trade may stand in the following proportions &#8211; the North West Company hold about eleven fourteenths, the Hudson Bay Co. one seventh, and the several oppositions from Canada one fourteenth.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">The Servants of the Hudson Bay are mostly from the Orkneys, and generally speaking a set of plain, honest, industrious fellows; who lay more stress on the honor of serving an honourable Company than any encouragement allowed their best endeavours in that Service &#8211; the views of the better sort, who are commonly good traders, seem more influenced by ambition than avarice.  The pompous titles, or rather Epithets, of Governors and Chiefs of Stockade Forts and log houses, with the trifling Salaries of, from thirty to, a hundred pounds with a few paltry perquisites</p>

